     1	# Data Model
     2	
     3	This chapter defines the shape of the values that flow through the
     4	EDEN protocol. For each entity it gives the intent, the fields, the
     5	required/optional split, and the structural invariants that MUST
     6	hold independent of any behavioral contract.
     7	
     8	Each entity also has a companion JSON Schema under
     9	[`schemas/`](schemas/). The prose in this chapter and the schema are
    10	normatively paired: an implementation's data MUST satisfy both. Where
    11	one is more restrictive than the other, the stricter constraint
    12	applies.
    13	
    14	Behavioral concerns — when fields may change, which transitions are
    15	permitted, what guarantees the surrounding store must offer — are
    16	specified in Chapters [`04-task-protocol.md`](04-task-protocol.md),
    17	[`05-event-protocol.md`](05-event-protocol.md),
    18	[`06-integrator.md`](06-integrator.md), and
    19	[`08-storage.md`](08-storage.md).
    20	
    21	## 1. Common types
    22	
    23	### 1.1 Identifiers
    24	
    25	Entity identifiers (`task_id`, `trial_id`, `proposal_id`,
    26	`event_id`) are opaque strings. They MUST be unique within the store
    27	that issues them. The protocol does not mandate a specific format;
    28	implementations MAY use integers rendered as strings, UUIDs, or
    29	other opaque values, so long as equality comparison is
    30	well-defined.
    31	
    32	### 1.2 Timestamps
    33	
    34	All timestamps in protocol messages MUST be RFC 3339 strings in
    35	UTC with second-or-better precision (e.g. `2026-04-23T18:04:01Z`).
    36	Offset timestamps (e.g. `…-07:00`) MUST NOT be used on the wire:
    37	every persisted timestamp MUST end with the literal `Z` suffix. A
    38	consumer MUST NOT assume timestamps are strictly monotonic across
    39	entities; ordering is established by the event log, not by
    40	timestamps.
    41	
    42	### 1.3 Metric values
    43	
    44	A metric value is one of: a JSON number (for `integer` or `real`
    45	types), a JSON string (for `text` type), or `null` (when the
    46	evaluator declined to report). Implementations MUST reject metric
    47	values whose JSON type does not match the declared metrics-schema
    48	type.
    49	
    50	The `integer` and `real` metric types both travel the wire as JSON
    51	numbers; they are distinguished by what values each admits:
    52	
    53	- **`integer`** — a JSON number whose value is an integer (no
    54	  fractional component). Wire forms such as `3`, `-7`, or `1.0` are
    55	  accepted; `1.5` MUST be rejected. A conforming orchestrator MUST
    56	  validate this constraint when persisting a metrics payload.
    57	- **`real`** — any JSON number, including values with a fractional
    58	  component.
    59	- **`text`** — a JSON string.
    60	- **`null`** — allowed for any declared type when the evaluator
    61	  declined to report that metric.
    62	
    63	### 1.4 Git references
    64	
    65	Commit SHAs are lowercase hexadecimal strings of an
    66	implementation-declared length (minimum 40 characters for SHA-1; 64
    67	for SHA-256). Branch names follow the namespaces defined in
    68	[`01-concepts.md`](01-concepts.md) §9.
    69	
    70	### 1.5 URIs
    71	
    72	Artifact locations are URIs. The protocol does not mandate a scheme;
    73	file URLs, S3 URLs, or custom schemes are permitted. A conforming
    74	artifact store MUST document which schemes it issues.
    75	
    76	## 2. Experiment config
    77	
    78	Schema: [`schemas/experiment-config.schema.json`](schemas/experiment-config.schema.json).
    79	
    80	An experiment config is the declarative input to an experiment. It
    81	is authored by a user (or generated by tooling) and persisted
    82	alongside the experiment.
    83	
    84	The protocol defines only the **host-mechanism-independent core** of
    85	the config — fields that every conforming implementation needs to
    86	observe the same semantics. How roles are bound (local subprocess,
    87	HTTP service, in-process adapter, …) is outside this chapter's
    88	scope; role binding is specified alongside the role contracts in
    89	[`03-roles.md`](03-roles.md) (Phase 2). Until then, implementations
    90	MAY carry role-binding information as additional top-level fields
    91	without violating this chapter.
    92	
    93	### 2.1 Required fields
    94	
    95	| Field | Type | Description |
    96	|---|---|---|
    97	| `parallel_trials` | integer ≥ 1 | Maximum number of trials that MAY be in flight simultaneously. |
    98	| `max_trials` | integer ≥ 1 | Hard ceiling on the number of trials attempted. |
    99	| `max_wall_time` | duration | Hard ceiling on elapsed wall time. Format: a positive integer followed by one of `s`, `m`, `h`, `d`. |
   100	| `metrics_schema` | object | A metrics schema (§6). MUST be non-empty. |
   101	| `objective` | object | An objective spec (§2.2). |
   102	
   103	### 2.2 Objective spec
   104	
   105	| Field | Type | Description |
   106	|---|---|---|
   107	| `expr` | string | A scalar expression over fields of `metrics_schema`. |
   108	| `direction` | string | Either `"maximize"` or `"minimize"`. |
   109	
   110	The expression language is implementation-defined but MUST treat
   111	metric field names as the free variables. A conforming orchestrator
   112	MUST reject an objective expression that references a name absent
   113	from `metrics_schema`.
   114	
   115	### 2.3 Optional fields
   116	
   117	| Field | Type | Default | Description |
   118	|---|---|---|---|
   119	| `convergence_window` | integer ≥ 1 | (none) | Terminate if the objective has not improved in this many trials. |
   120	| `target_condition` | string | (none) | A condition over metrics; when satisfied, the experiment terminates early. |
   121	
   122	### 2.4 Additional top-level fields
   123	
   124	Implementations MAY define additional top-level fields for role
   125	binding and implementation-specific tuning. The experiment-config
   126	schema does not restrict unknown top-level fields; a conforming
   127	orchestrator MUST NOT reject a config solely because it carries
   128	fields this chapter does not define. This forward-compatibility
   129	rule is intentional: it lets role-binding semantics land in
   130	[`03-roles.md`](03-roles.md) without breaking previously-valid
   131	configs.
   132	
   133	An implementation SHOULD document which additional top-level fields
   134	it consumes.
   135	
   136	## 3. Task
   137	
   138	Schema: [`schemas/task.schema.json`](schemas/task.schema.json).
   139	
   140	A task is a work item. It is persisted in the task store and
   141	advances through a state machine defined in
   142	[`04-task-protocol.md`](04-task-protocol.md); this section defines
   143	only its shape.
   144	
   145	### 3.1 Fields
   146	
   147	| Field | Required | Type | Description |
   148	|---|---|---|---|
   149	| `task_id` | yes | string | Unique identifier. |
   150	| `kind` | yes | string | One of `"plan"`, `"implement"`, `"evaluate"`. |
   151	| `state` | yes | string | See §3.2. |
   152	| `payload` | yes | object | Kind-specific payload (§3.3). |
   153	| `claim` | no | object | Present iff the task is currently claimed (§3.4). |
   154	| `created_at` | yes | timestamp | When the task was created. |
   155	| `updated_at` | yes | timestamp | Most recent state change. |
   156	
   157	### 3.2 State values
   158	
   159	The `state` field MUST be one of `"pending"`, `"claimed"`,
   160	`"submitted"`, `"completed"`, `"failed"`. The legal transitions
   161	between these states are defined in
   162	[`04-task-protocol.md`](04-task-protocol.md). The data model
   163	constrains only that the value be one of the listed strings.
   164	
   165	### 3.3 Payload shape
   166	
   167	The `payload` object's shape depends on `kind`.
   168	
   169	- `"plan"` — MUST contain `experiment_id` (string). MAY contain
   170	  planner-specific hints.
   171	- `"implement"` — MUST contain `proposal_id` (string) referring to
   172	  a proposal with `state == "ready"` at the time of dispatch.
   173	- `"evaluate"` — MUST contain `trial_id` (string) referring to a
   174	  trial with `status == "starting"` and a `commit_sha` set.
   175	
   176	### 3.4 Claim object
   177	
   178	| Field | Required | Type | Description |
   179	|---|---|---|---|
   180	| `token` | yes | string | Opaque unforgeable claim token. |
   181	| `worker_id` | yes | string | Opaque identifier for the claiming worker. |
   182	| `claimed_at` | yes | timestamp | When the claim was issued. |
   183	| `expires_at` | no | timestamp | When the task store MAY reclaim. |
   184	
   185	The `claim` field MUST be present when `state == "claimed"`, and MUST
   186	NOT be present for any other state. The schema in
   187	[`schemas/task.schema.json`](schemas/task.schema.json) enforces this
   188	mutual exclusion.
   189	
   190	## 4. Event
   191	
   192	Schema: [`schemas/event.schema.json`](schemas/event.schema.json).
   193	
   194	An event records a state change. Events are immutable once appended.
   195	
   196	### 4.1 Envelope
   197	
   198	Every event MUST provide this envelope:
   199	
   200	| Field | Required | Type | Description |
   201	|---|---|---|---|
   202	| `event_id` | yes | string | Unique identifier within the log. |
   203	| `type` | yes | string | A dotted type name, e.g. `task.claimed`, `trial.evaluated`. |
   204	| `occurred_at` | yes | timestamp | When the state change happened. |
   205	| `experiment_id` | yes | string | The experiment this event belongs to. |
   206	| `data` | yes | object | Type-specific payload (§4.2). |
   207	
   208	### 4.2 Type-specific payload
   209	
   210	Each event `type` corresponds to a shape under `data`. The full
   211	enumeration of types is defined in
   212	[`05-event-protocol.md`](05-event-protocol.md); at this layer, the
   213	data model requires only that `data` be a JSON object and that its
   214	shape match the registered schema for the event's `type`.
   215	
   216	### 4.3 Ordering
   217	
   218	Events within a single experiment MUST form a total order consistent
   219	with causality: if event B describes a state change that depended
   220	on a state recorded by event A, A MUST precede B in the log. The
   221	ordering mechanism is a storage concern
   222	([`08-storage.md`](08-storage.md)).
   223	
   224	## 5. Proposal
   225	
   226	Schema: [`schemas/proposal.schema.json`](schemas/proposal.schema.json).
   227	
   228	A proposal is the planner's output.
   229	
   230	### 5.1 Fields
   231	
   232	| Field | Required | Type | Description |
   233	|---|---|---|---|
   234	| `proposal_id` | yes | string | Unique identifier. |
   235	| `experiment_id` | yes | string | The experiment this proposal belongs to. |
   236	| `slug` | yes | string | Human-readable short label. MUST match `^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9-]*$`. |
   237	| `priority` | yes | number | Ordering hint; higher dispatches earlier. |
   238	| `parent_commits` | yes | array of SHA | One or more commit SHAs the proposal is based on. |
   239	| `artifacts_uri` | yes | string (URI) | Where the planner's output documents live. |
   240	| `state` | yes | string | One of `"drafting"`, `"ready"`, `"dispatched"`, `"completed"`. |
   241	| `created_at` | yes | timestamp | When the proposal was created. |
   242	
   243	### 5.2 Parent commits
   244	
   245	`parent_commits` MUST contain at least one SHA. Each SHA MUST name a
   246	commit reachable from the experiment's starting commit on `main` or
   247	from an already-completed trial on the canonical trial lineage.
   248	
   249	## 6. Metrics schema
   250	
   251	Schema: [`schemas/metrics-schema.schema.json`](schemas/metrics-schema.schema.json).
   252	
   253	A metrics schema is a mapping from metric name to storage type. It
   254	appears as the `metrics_schema` field of an experiment config and is
   255	used to validate every metrics payload the evaluator produces.
   256	
   257	### 6.1 Shape
   258	
   259	The metrics schema is a JSON object whose keys are metric names and
   260	whose values are type strings.
   261	
   262	- A metric name MUST match `^[A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_]*$`.
   263	- A type value MUST be one of `"integer"`, `"real"`, `"text"`.
   264	- A metrics schema MUST have at least one entry.
   265	
   266	### 6.2 Reserved names
   267	
   268	The names `trial_id`, `commit_sha`, `parent_commits`, `branch`,
   269	`status`, `artifacts_uri`, `description`, `timestamp`, `started_at`,
   270	`completed_at` are reserved by the protocol for use on the trial
   271	object and MUST NOT appear in a metrics schema.
   272	
   273	## 7. Trial
   274	
   275	Schema: [`schemas/trial.schema.json`](schemas/trial.schema.json).
   276	
   277	A trial is one completed attempt.
   278	
   279	### 7.1 Fields
   280	
   281	| Field | Required | Type | Description |
   282	|---|---|---|---|
   283	| `trial_id` | yes | string | Unique identifier. |
   284	| `experiment_id` | yes | string | The experiment this trial belongs to. |
   285	| `proposal_id` | yes | string | The proposal that produced this trial. |
   286	| `status` | yes | string | One of `"starting"`, `"success"`, `"error"`, `"eval_error"`. |
   287	| `parent_commits` | yes | array of SHA | Inherited from the proposal. |
   288	| `branch` | no | string | Worker branch under `work/*`. Present once the implementer starts. |
   289	| `commit_sha` | no | string | Worker-branch tip SHA. Present once the implementer completes. |
   290	| `trial_commit_sha` | no | string | Canonical-lineage SHA under `trial/*`. Present once the integrator has promoted the trial. |
   291	| `artifacts_uri` | no | string (URI) | Where the trial's artifacts live. |
   292	| `description` | no | string | Human-readable summary. |
   293	| `metrics` | no | object | Metrics payload; shape dictated by the experiment's metrics schema. |
   294	| `started_at` | yes | timestamp | When the implementer began. |
   295	| `completed_at` | no | timestamp | When the evaluator submitted. |
   296	
   297	### 7.2 Metrics payload
   298	
   299	If present, `metrics` MUST be an object whose keys are a subset of
   300	the declared metrics-schema keys and whose values match the declared
   301	types (§1.3) or are `null`. Because the metrics-schema is
   302	per-experiment, [`schemas/trial.schema.json`](schemas/trial.schema.json)
   303	cannot express this constraint generically and leaves `metrics` as
   304	an open object; the per-metric type check is a runtime responsibility
   305	of the orchestrator. A conforming orchestrator MUST reject a metrics
   306	payload that violates the experiment's metrics-schema, and MUST NOT
   307	record the trial as `"success"` in that case.
   308	
   309	### 7.3 Status transitions
   310	
   311	Trial status transitions are behavioral and are defined alongside
   312	the task and event protocols in
   313	[`04-task-protocol.md`](04-task-protocol.md). The data model
   314	constrains only that the status be one of the listed strings.
   315	
   316	## 8. Invariants across entities
   317	
   318	This section collects structural invariants that span multiple
   319	entities. Behavioral invariants (claim semantics, transactional
   320	event writes) live in the corresponding behavior chapters.
   321	
   322	1. **Identifier scope.** `task_id`, `proposal_id`, `trial_id`, and
   323	   `event_id` MUST each be unique within a single experiment.
   324	   Uniqueness across experiments is not required by the protocol
   325	   but is RECOMMENDED when an implementation shares a store across
   326	   experiments.
   327	2. **Reference integrity.** Every `proposal_id` referenced by a
   328	   task payload or trial MUST name a proposal persisted in the
   329	   store before the reference is written. Every `trial_id`
   330	   referenced by an `evaluate` task MUST exist with
   331	   `status == "starting"` at dispatch time.
   332	3. **Metrics/schema conformance.** Every metrics payload persisted
   333	   on a trial MUST validate against the experiment's
   334	   `metrics_schema` (§6).
   335	4. **Canonical-lineage single-writer.** Only the integrator MAY
   336	   write to `trial_commit_sha` on a trial. Workers MUST NOT set or
   337	   modify this field directly.
   338	5. **Claim uniqueness.** A task MAY have at most one active
   339	   `claim` object at any time.

